problem.markdown:
>>Which of the following are true about <i>k</i>-fold cross-validation?<<

[x] A. Increase in <i>k</i> will result in more time required to cross-validate the result {{ selected: A. Correct}}
[x] B. Higher values of <i>k</i> will result in higher confidence on the cross-validation results {{selected: B. Correct}}
[x] C. In cross-validation, you can run the experiments sequentially and change the hyper-parameters of the next experiments based on the results of the previous experiments {{selected: C. Correct}}
[ ] D. None of the above are true {{selected: D. Incorrect answer: Larger <i>k</i> value means less bias towards overestimating the true expected error (as training folds will be closer to the total dataset) and higher running time (as you are getting closer to the limit case: <i>k</i>=number of training samples).}}

{{ ((A B C D)) D is not compatible with A,B,C. }}
